reviews.text: This museum gave a very brief overview of the maritime industry in Croatia. If visiting, I suggest purchasing the Dubrovnik card which will allow entry to this and other museums.
An interesting range of exhibits and the museum is worth a visit if you have a few days in Dubrovnik.

This is a nice place to visit if you're on the Dubrovnik Card.
Lots of nice exhibits, takes you back in time though the perspective of the most important trade in Dubrovnik's history.

Worth checking out if you've purchased the Dubrovnik pass, otherwise quite expensive. Lots of interesting maritime history directly related to the area. You're not permitted to take pictures (why?) I still took a couple.. Ssshhhhh ;)
Great presentation in very fitting environment

Very reasonable 10 Euro for an audio tour of the palace. I would highly recommend to anyone! There are kids audio options and if you are really interested in something you can get even more information via audio. The staff are SUPER friendly and there is a cloakroom for your bag and coats.

Beautiful palace that just inspires awe at every turn. To be among such great pieces of work and history is truly humbling.

This place is very befitting of the title "Royal" and is a marvel with the intricacies of the paintings, sculptures, and works of art scattered throughout.

The admission is fairly priced and comes with a free audio tour that provides nuggets of information on the various rooms and history associated with them. Additionally, the tour gives you options of learning the extra facts relating to a sculpture and/or painting.

I really feel like you could come here 2 or 3 times and still learn or see something new here. Absolutely beautiful in hundreds of ways, witnessing this building and all its treasures firsthand is something spectacular. Pictures don't do it justice.

Anything to do with Amsterdam is already good enough for me. Add to that a chance to take in the Royal Palace, the cherry has been placed on my tourism cake. 

Taking a walking tour was well worth it. We learned so much from our guide, it truly made the experience memorable.

If you have the time, why not do it? The architecture that surrounds the area alone, is well worth it.

First of all, if you're into interesting buildings, you can never go wrong with palaces. This type of buildings are always the place of many interesting stories. This city hall turned palace during the reign of Napoleon is no different. Large halls full of exquisite art and the most expensive furniture give you a peek at how it is to be a dignitary in the Netherlands. The excellent audio tour (with a special version for kids) in a dozen languages that allows you to wander through the halls in your own tempo makes it a five star to visit. No rush, just interesting history.

It’s amazing that you’re able to walk in and explore the actual Royal Palace! There’s a wide range of different rooms - all with unique snippets of history attached. Joy for the whole family - would definitely recommend visiting it if you’re in Amsterdam.

Unlike many other sightseeing places, this one is very kid- and English-friendly. Kids get their own audio guide and a little necklace to fill out to keep them interested. For adults there are various language available - including English.

What a fun place to go with a family that is really hungry and ready for some entertainment. This dining experience was entertaining from the start. Immediately as you get to the restaurant outside you have beautiful Japanese garden with some gorgeous prize-winning goldfishes. They kids had so much fun looking at them swimming and everything.  After all of that excitement we were able to be seated at a Japanese Hibachi Table with another family and kids so my children had a lot of fun interacting with everyone else around the table. As the chef came in he quickly started his show and it was fun interactive and very energetic. There was so much food!!!! Your portions are very large so make sure you come hungry. the typical Hibachi chicken dinner included rice vegetables and before that you get to have soup and salad. The only reason I took a star of was that the food was not as flavorful or authentic as I am used to but for being Japanese attraction chain spot it was sort of expected to be a little Bland however it was perfect for kiddos taste buds.

The food is surprisingly better than one might think. The salad that comes out with the soup prior to the meal is delicious I really like the dressing here. I did not care for the sushi as it did not seem as fresh as some places. The steak and chicken combo I ordered was well-cooked and affordable.

We arrived around 5:30, no one else in the dining area except for a group that was finishing up. We waited 15-20min before getting our drinks. A party of 16 arrived after we got our drinks. We had already ordered when another group joined our table. We still had not received our salads or soup an HOUR after being seated, but the party’s food was being cooked and served. Poor management. We were told that the party arrived before us, when they actually MOVED us from the table the party was sitting at to serve us quicker. The manager that I spoke with said “they knew what they wanted to eat, they had a list” I DON’T CARE if they had a list, we had ordered our food BEFORE the party placed their order. Waiting an hour and not receiving soups and salads is unacceptable in my book.

This place has always been pretty good. However the service has really gone down hill. No refills for the entire meal. Wrong food served. Appetizers brought after meal. Very small portions. Time to search for new place to eat.

Yes yes!! Best sushi presentation in Tennessee. Chef Boy knows how to make a birthday special. I told him to surprise me and yes I was surprised with a great sushi dinner.. will always be my go to place for sushi!!

Very small museum, cool knowledgeable guides that seem to master a lot of the countrie's historic, traditional and mythological stories. In an hour you can see most part of it. There is a little shop outside of the museum where you can buy some artifacts that are also available elsewhere at lesser price.
I like this place but I would love it if it had enough traditional and local object. I think it doesn't represent enough the national heritage

I loved visiting this museum. I wish I could've taken pictures. Nevertheless, our tour guide, William Dayo, was very well versed in each of the exhibits. It was really nice to have someone with us who gave us in depth information on what we were viewing. It gave us a deeper understanding and appreciation for each of the artifacts.
It was nice. The museum has a lot to offer in cultural history and I was happy to see them opened on a Sunday.

This museum continues the tradition of equating Western African culture and history mainly with masks (sarcasm). It could almost be interchangeable with the museum's in Dakar and Bamako except they both have a second floor dedicated to textiles. 

Granted, the masks are interesting and high quality, but they are completely decontextualized with cryptic captions an little explanation tying anything together.

There is one table showing the evolution of money that was nice. 

It's one of the few times I wished there was a museum gift shop with some books. 

Weirdly they don't allow photography either, as if history should be hidden. 

Avoid the restaurant out back it is way overpriced and there are better maquis around.

Невелика синагога «Бейт-Тфіла Біньямін» була збудована 1923 року на пожертвування родини Біньяміна Шапіро. 1938 року на будинку було встановлено меморіальну дошку з написом, виконаним єврейськими літерами німецькою мовою (не їдишем). Це свідчить про те, наскільки чернівецькі євреї були асимільовані в німецькомовну культуру навіть у період румунського правління, яке чинило опір німецькому культурному впливу. В період з 1959 по 1994 рр. вона була єдиною діючою синагогою в місті. Особливу цінність становлять її внутрішні розписи, виконані невідомим чернівецьким художником. Розписи вкривають практично весь внутрішній простір приміщення. За своєю самобутністю та художнім рівнем ці розписи є визначним зразком релігійної єврейської творчості Східної Європи.
בית כנסת
Дом Родной!!!

Are you a lover of modern art of all mediums? Are you interested in Slovenian artists and the inspiration behind their works? If so, this museum is not to be missed. There are many interesting paintings, sculptures, video artworks, and other curiosities. If you are squeamish about you or your children seeing nudity, this gallery may not be your cup of tea. But if you are comfortable seeing a few naked body art works sprinkled in with the other art work, do stop by. The museum has a downstairs coffee bar/lounge and lecture hall for talks.  I really enjoyed the museum and its art works.

Half of the space is permanent exhibition and other half is actual and temporary, usually open three times a year for a few months; always interesting topic. 
Otherwise calm and chilly space, where time and thoughts run slower tempo.

I was left speechless. The exhibits are so beautifully pieced together that it is almost impossible to peel your eyes off them. You will need about an hour to go through the whole gallery, after which you can relax in the cafè bellow the gallery itself. The gallery also provides a student discount, so be sure to bring your students' card!

Beautiful bulging and interesting permanent collection. You will need 30 minutes-1 hour to see it all. The temporary exhibition space is big and well organised. The thicket costs only 5 euros: an extra reason to have this insight into modern Slovenia. Visit the coffee downstairs if you have a little time.
One of my favourite places in Ljubljana to have a nice cup of coffee or tea and stay close to modern art. Highly recommended.

Loved the vibe, lots of older hip hop hits played at a reasonable volume and the bar wasn't too crowded. Bartenders were fast getting drinks, though the drinks were quite expensive at $8.50 for a tequila shot. The atmosphere is much chiller than the other downtown bars, which made the pricing a bit more palatable.
Great experience. The customer service was excellent. We went during restaurant week and there was a variety of selections. The cheese fritters were exceptional. We would visit again.
INCREDIBLE!!! Everything we ordered was just amazing! Cannot recommend enough! Great friendly service, romantic environment, and did I mention the food? Can't wait to go back! So impressed!
The duck breast was good.  I strongly recommend it.  But the dessert wasn't worth it.  It was barely okay.
Great service and awesome food, we'll be going back.
Good place to go with family, specially on weekends. Excellent sort of stores, easy access, clean and with plenty of bathroom. The only problem is that needs more seats on the food court.

I love the Arndale. You can find every price range and everything. Amazing choice of food places. Seems to be well run. Well done Manchester for having such a really good sgopping place. Information desks well placed. Cant grumble at all.

Beautiful place to visit and shop. Big parking, I recommend you pinpoint your car on map when you park lol. The shopping center is magnificent. Very beautiful and unique in style. I loved it. Excellent glass ceilings, a beautiful view from all side. I recommend visiting this place and shopping from it

Huge shopping mall.Varied choice of stores.Right in city centre with tram stops providing access to all sides.
You can spend hours here and enjoy the cafes and restaurants too.
A better selection of restaurants would be nice as its beyond boring to see the same name brands everywhere. The location then becomes irrelevant, other than that it's a standard shopping centre.

Beautiful place to visit. One of the best displayed Museums I've seen. Manageable size and friendly knowledgeable volunteers. You can avoid the Holocaust section.  Interesting even if not interested! Nice cafe too.

Such a brilliant museum. Gives a brief introduction to the faith. The main part of the museum gives a brilliant insight into the stories and history of Jewish people in Britain, from the Normon conquest to modern day. There is a brilliant balance between the general history and personal experiences. It taught me so much I never knew. Also visited the exhibition "Jews, Money, Myth". So, so interesting and insightful! Wonderfully curated. There was printed texts on the walls of a conversation between the director and curator, giving insight into the reasons for what was exhibited and what was not and the reasons why. I would definitely recommend.

Good insight into Jewish history. Very large section on London history some of which is good some of which is terrible (suffering, poverty) - reflected well. As to whether to immerse yourself? Wait till they have exhibition or a peculiar on So you get to see one more floor
A well appointed museum that is easy to see in 4 hours. The displays are well lit and the descriptions easily read. Well worth the visit
Nice and interesting museum full of Jewish and Israeli history and even more.  Small cafe for a quick lunch. Would recommend it as Camden Market very near by. Wish the ticket price was lower..
